defaultLaw Commission – Written evidencedefault&#xa0;defaultExecutive Summary
default&#xa0;
defaultThe principal matters arising from the evidence of the Law Commission (“the Commission”) may be summarised as follows:
default&#xa0;
default(1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Law Commission (“the Commission”) shares the objectives of Government to make the law more accessible and to remove obsolete legislation from the statute book.
default&#xa0;
default(2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Commission has a statutory duty under section 3(1) of the Law Commissions Act 1965 to keep under review all the law of England and Wales with a view, inter alia, to the repeal of obsolete and unnecessary enactments. Since 1965 it has promoted the repeal of over 3000 statutes and many thousands of other provisions.
default&#xa0;
default(3)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn performing this work, the Commission has considerable experience and expertise, is able to employ a fast track Parliamentary procedure and has the trust of Parliament.
default&#xa0;
default(4)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Triennial Review of the Commission concluded in July 2013 that it is essential that the Law Commission, an expert, independent body, should continue to perform this function
default&#xa0;
default(5)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe powers proposed in clauses 50-57, 62 and schedule 16 of the Bill duplicate the provisions in the Law Commissions Act 1965 and do not provide the advantages of the Commission’s statute law repeal procedure. 
default&#xa0;
default(6)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Commission is deeply concerned at the impact of being a statutory 
defaultconsultee
default.  It could not perform this role adequately and continue with its own repeal work.
default&#xa0;
default(7)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGiven the specialist nature of statute law repeal work, the importance of accuracy and the need to have an in depth understanding of the consequences of repeal, the Commission proposes that the better course for primary legislation would be to adapt and improve the existing Statute Law Repeal procedure to meet changing needs.
default&#xa0;
default(8)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis would not require legislative change, would be more cost effective and provide legal certainty. 
default&#xa0;
default(9)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is preferable that the repeal of primary legislation be achieved by the existing Statute Law Repeal procedure employing an Act of Parliament as opposed to Ministerial powers.
default&#xa0;
default(10)
default 
defaultThere already exist alternative mechanisms for the repeal of secondary legislation. For this reason the Commission does not currently focus on secondary legislation. It would not be able to perform adequately the role of statutory 
defaultconsultee
default in relation to secondary legislation within existing resources.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe evidence ends with answers to certain specific questions posed by the Committee.  
